SIMPLE: switch
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Switch
<hw>Switch</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OD.
<ets>swick</ets> a scourage, a whip. Cf. <er>Swink</er>,
<er>Swing</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small, flexible twig or
rod.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mauritania, on the fifth medal, leads a horse with something like
a thread; in her other hand she holds a <qex>switch</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Railways)</fld> <def>A movable part of a rail; or
of opposite rails, for transferring cars from one track to
another.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A separate mass or trees of hair, or of some
substance (at jute) made to resemble hair, worn on the head by
women.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Elec.)</fld> <def>A device for shifting an electric
current to another circuit, or for making and breaking a
circuit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Safety switch</b></col> <fld>(Railways)</fld>, <cd>a form
of switch contrived to prevent or lessen the danger of derailment of
trains.</cd> -- <col><b>Switch back</b></col> <fld>(Railways)</fld>,
<cd>an arrangement of tracks whereby elevations otherwise insurmountable
are passed. The track ascends by a series of zigzags, the engine running
alternately forward and back, until the summit is reached.</cd> --
<col><b>Switch board</b></col> <fld>(Elec.)</fld>, <cd>a collection of
switches in one piece of apparatus, so arranged that a number of
circuits may be connected or combined in any desired manner.</cd><--
need "switchboard" for telephony --> -- <col><b>Switch grass</b></col>.
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Grass</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Switch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Switch
<hw>Switch</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Switched</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Switching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike with a
switch or small flexible rod; to whip.</def>
<rj><au>Chapman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To swing or whisk; <as>as, to <ex>switch</ex> a
cane</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To trim, <as>as, a hedge</as>.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To turn from one railway track to another; to
transfer by a switch; -- generally with <xex>off</xex>, <xex>from</xex>,
etc.; <as>as, to <ex>switch</ex> off a train; to <ex>switch</ex> a car
from one track to another</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>To shift to another
circuit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Switch</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Switch
<hw>Switch</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To walk with a jerk.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>switchboard</ent>⟦br⟧
